  <div id="dissentUhl">
    <p>I respectfully dissent from the majority.</p>

    <p>To me its impossible to escape the facts in this case that the Respondent failed to honor a subpoena in
    94-DB-024 and later lied when asked if he received the subpoena.  The record and testimony show that Respondent
    picked up the subpoena!</p>

    <p>He also lied when he notified the Disciplinary Board that he "gave Ms Davis her file some time in November or
    December and I assumed that matter was concluded at that point".  Even the committee noted that is answers are
    inconsistent.</p>

    <p>Mr. Dixon has not retained any correspondence concerning the complaint nor documentation concerning the return
    of the file to Ms. Davis.</p>

    <p>The committee specifically notes that Mr. Dixon did not make the effort to respond in writing to the subpoena
    nor indicate to the office of Disciplinary Counsel that the subject matter of the subpoena had been satisfied.</p>

    <p>In its Opinion  Hearing Committee, in 94-DB-024, wrote, "Mr.  Dixon apparently takes a cavalier attitude towards
    responding requests or to subpoenas.  His practices indicate if not a willful refusal to comply with the rules of
    the Disciplinary Counsel, at least, a casual indifference to or negligence in the obligations attendant to the
    practice of Law".  "The Committee does not find that Mr.  Dixon's refusal to honor the subpoena was a willful or
    deliberate act to circumvent the efforts of the Office of the Disciplinary Counsel or to hide, conceal or
    misrepresent evidence in this matter". "The Committee's impression of Mr. Dixon is that he is a very sloppy
    attorney who does not take his responsibilities to his clients or to the Bar very seriously".  The report goes on,
    "Mr.  Dixon was late for the Committee Hearing, which certainly should have been very important to him.  The
    Committee, however, feels that he was not late in a contemptuous manner, but <em>for some reason he cannot or does
    notpay apropriate attention to the selfous matters which the normal attorney would</em> <em>deem very
    important".</em></p>

    <p>And the committee report asks a closing question, "How this reflects on his private practice of law is
    unknown(?), but, certainly he does not take his professional responsibilities seriously enough".</p>

    <p>Findings of Facts by the Hearing Committee in 94-DB-009 the Respondent "his lack of thoroughness and preparation
    in readying for the August 26, 1991 trial date falls short of our perception of <b><u>"competent</u></b>
    <b><u>representation."</u></b> Furthermore, we find that Respondent failed to act with <b><u>'reasonable diligence
    and</u></b> <b><u>promptness"</u></b> in attempting to present the evidence to the Court at the trial on the
    merits.</p>

    <p>In 94-DB-024 &amp; 94-DB-009.</p>

    <p>Mitigating factors included the fact that there were no prior disciplinary record.  And the length of the time
    of the onset of the complaints and the resolution of the matter(s).</p>

    <h2>PRIOR DISCIPLINE..</h2>

    <p>In matter of prior discipline, I understand how this subject might not get much import or attention when taken
    up as if it were one (1) complaint.  It is a consolidation of two (2) complaints- of types and charges.  However,
    when confronted with the entire record, one cannot dismiss the two (2) separate complaints as one (1) complaint One
    complaint follows the other.  A string of rules violations that were interrupted, by these two complaints.  The
    consolidation is acknowledgement of the rules violation(s) in two separate instances.</p>

    <p>It may been prior discipline, nevertheless, Respondent has had problems with the disciplinary system</p>

    <p>on two (2) occasions Both cases show a pattern of misconduct.</p>

    <h2>LENGTH OF TIME FOR THE RESOLUTION OF BOTH CASES.</h2>

    <p>The facts indicate the Respondent had a major part in the delays, and obstruction of the proceedings involved in
    the resolution of both complaints!</p>

    <p>The facts indicate that it should be an aggravating factor, not a mitigating one.</p>

    <h2>REFUSAL TO ACKNOWLEDGE THE WRONGFUL NATURE OF THE CONDUCT.</h2>

    <p>The facts in the record reflect that he has not acknowledged the wrongful nature of the conduct.  And is an
    aggravating factor</p>

    <h2>THE RESPONSIBILITY LAWYERS OWE TO THE COURT, PROFESSION &amp; PUBLIC.</h2>

    <p>In both cases Finding of facts and Conclusions of Law do not address the responsibilities Lawyers owe to the
    Courts, the Profession and to the Public.</p>

    <p>What message are we sending to the Profession and the Public, when failure to honor a subpena is given a public
    reprimand?</p>

    <p>What about the profession, is it better off now that lies are given a reprimand?  And is it better off for
    failure to respond to a subpoena receives public reprimand?</p>

    <p>A to the LAW, when the Respondent, based on the facts, lied when he made statements and gave evidence?  And, the
    sanction is a reprimand!  How outrageous!</p>

    <p>As a citizen member of the Board I am saddened to see subpoena treated as it was in this case.</p>

    <h2>  RECOMMENDED SANCTIONS</h2>

    <p class="Bodycopy">After reading the record my recommendations are:</p>

    <p class="Bodycopy"> 90 Day, suspension for the failure to respond to the subpena and the lying of respondent as to
    facts and statements.</p>

    <p class="Bodycopy"> After the suspension term, a one (1) year probation.  I apply this probation period as a
    result of the -two (2) formal charges and the pattern of misconduct.</p>

    <p class="Bodycopy">He  extra 6 CLE credits, in the area of law office management for solo practitioners.  And such
    credits to be above and beyond the mandatory 15 hours required.  The credits completed within six (6) months.</p>

